<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abutiloides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. abutiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar in their liana habit, leaves grey-tomentose or sericeous beneath, their oblong-elliptic sepals and their inflorescences which have a tendency to become leafy and racemose or even paniculate towards the branch tips. They are best distinguished by the sepal indumentum, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having sericeous sepals while those of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abutiloides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. abutiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are glabrous. The two species intergrade in the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Abapó">Abapo</normalizedToken>
area of Bolivia where their ranges overlap.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Records from Peru (Austin and Staples 1991: 273) are mostly errors for the very similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Kuntze" authorityName="Kuntze" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pearceana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea pearceana</emphasis>
Kuntze
</taxonomicName>
, which differs in little more than the relatively persistent elongate- oblong bracteoles.
</paragraph>
